    <title>Combined summary - BIP39 seeds</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T16:36:33.680577+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2018-December/016587.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>A conversation on the bitcoin-dev mailing list focused on the security concerns related to generating BIP39 phrases and ways to improve them. The debate touched upon using fake sources of randomness versus true random BIP39 sentences, and the importance of choosing the source of randomness carefully. Participants also discussed the effectiveness of 12-word recovery phrases compared to 32-byte BIP32 hexadecimal seeds, with some arguing that recovery phrases are more resilient for physical storage. However, there were concerns that some users may not take the importance of recovery phrases seriously enough, leading to loss or forgetfulness.The discussion addressed the need for improved methods of generating and storing BIP39 seeds and keys, with the forthcoming SLIP39 standard aiming to address some of these issues. The SLIP39 proposal by SatoshiLabs aims to improve the flexibility and security of multi-signature wallets by allowing users to split their seed phrases into multiple shares. The proposed standard seeks to enhance the current probabilities of generating valid BIP39 seeds from randomly chosen words through multiple share schemes.In an email thread from December 26, 2018, Aymeric Vitte expressed concern that even with a tool like the one being discussed, users could be misled into believing they have found the correct seed phrase and become stuck trying to find their keys using BIP44/49. However, the creator of the tool clarified that it looks up all possible combinations and only confirms the correctness of a phrase if it has been used before on the blockchain. The tool was designed to generate a BIP39 phrase that can be used with any BIP39 wallet and the idea was deemed reasonable.The conversation also discussed the probability of generating a "valid" BIP39 seed from randomly chosen words from a 2048-word dictionary. Pavol Rusnak, an engineer at Coinbase, provided the probabilities for 12 and 24 words, which are 1:16 and 1:256, respectively. The email exchange also included links to various tools and resources related to bitcoin transactions, Zcash wallets, and more.The discussion highlighted the need for caution when generating BIP39 phrases and the importance of choosing secure sources of randomness. It also underscored the need for improved methods of generating and storing BIP39 seeds and keys, with the forthcoming SLIP39 standard expected to address some of these issues.</summary>
